< review>
We go almost every Sunday after church with the our kids and have some awesome food and enjoy having Bryan waiting on us. He is so professional and fast on service. We recommend the beef  enchilada plate and camarones mexicanos. The kids get nice portions and have tried almost every meal on the kids menu. Also kids menu items are 99cents on sundays. You also get chips, salsa, and refried beans with tasty white cheese for an appetizer and end the meal with a sweet desert. We got churos and vanilla ice cream last time we went. Go see Bryan and the gang and have a great meal on sundays.</review>

<Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
I've been going here for 20+ years and I have been absolutely pleased Every Time.
The service is impeccable, they are: Friendly, Courteous, Prompt and Eager to Please.
The food is always: Fresh, Hot and Tasty.
They have all the Mexican food classics. Children are welcome. They love to host a birthday dinner for any age. Their drinks are also excellent.
The Camarones Mexicanos are so good I have a hard time ordering anything else, and a Tequila Popper always goes well with the bill.
This is always the first restaurant in Redding that I recommend.< /Review>

< Text>
At more than 3,500 acres, Bidwell Park is one of the area‚Äôs largest municipal parks. It offers visitors a variety of outdoor recreation options.

The park‚Äôs amenities include a nature center, lake, several impressive geological formations, abundant treed areas, and a popular municipal golf course that‚Äôs popular with cost-conscious golfers.

On the weekends during the warm spring and summer months, the park can draw sizable crowds. If you‚Äôd prefer to visit when the masses are at work or still in bed, consider stopping by in the morning during the week.< /Text>

< review>
I am very sad to have to post this but it is a safety issue. I have lived in Chico my whole life and have seen this park at its best and unfortunately it is at its worst right now. There are numerous illegal encampments that the City is doing absolutely nothing about. I have done volunteer clean ups in lower Bidwell park and the amount of trash, human fecal waste and drug paraphernalia is off the charts. Many years ago it was a safe place to enjoy with your family and friends. Now it is not a safe place to be at all. The criminal element is everywhere. If you still choose to go, please be aware of your surroundings at all times and don't venture off the trails. Keep a close eye on your children and pets as we numerous discarded hypodermic needles throughout the park.<//review>

< Review>
Family friendly park shaded by huge valley oak trees along Chico creek. This park earned it's namesake from location, as it is one mile from the historic pioneers' Bidwell Mansion. Surroundings are complete with a swimming area, horseshoe pit, playground, restrooms, and more! Worth checking out, bring the kid's and even Grandma! There is a trail from the estate extending all the way to Bidwell Park Five-Mile that is popularly jogged, walked, biked or skated!</Review>

< review>
This peaceful paradise which adorns charming Chico, CA, is a sight to behold. The lovely Bidwell Park boasts a natural swimming area easily accessible from several major streets and residential areas. This area is affectionately called One-Mile. Outdoor adventurers will also enjoy the paved road through the park which spans the area along Big Chico Creek. The recreation area has many attractions such as biking, hiking, walking, birdwatching as well as peaceful communing with nature. It is a must-see destination for all.</review>

Beautiful park! There is a biking and walking trail up either side of the creek and the a myriad of other trails in the woods.
There is a herd of goats that help keep the underbrush down and are kept in a fenced in spot.
Of note: there are a fair amount of homeless folks who use the park so don‚Äôt be surprised to see them around.</text>

< Rating>
5</Rating>
<Name>James Griffith<//Name>< Text>
The 3600 acre park is one of the largest municipal parks in the U-S. It stretches for miles from close to Chico's downtown (One Mile Area) to well up into the foothills miles out of town where nude swimming is tolerated in the cold waters of Chico creek. The park offers miles of hiking, biking and horseback riding trails and paths some of which are paved while others are dirt and more suited for trail bikes. A portion of the natural creek has been cemented and dammed to create a large area for swimming safely in the flowing creek waters. Bidwell Park is so beautiful it was used as a substitute for the English countryside the 1938 action classic, "The Adventures of Robin Hood" starring Erroll Flynn highlighted by the famous duel between Robin Hood and Little John staged over Chico Creek which is at the center of the park and provides water for the hundreds of stately mature California oak trees and dozens of other plants that make the park so special. If you visit Chico and don't spend time in the park, you are missing the one attraction that makes Chico truly unique.< /Text>

<Rating>5< /Rating><Review>My boyfriend took me here on our second date. We came for a picnic in September when it still felt like July. We ate under the trees, watched other people seek respite from the heat in the shade, the kids swim in the natural pool, and enjoyed the overall languid, California summer feel.

The park is a great space, with a lot of different options for different activities--swimming, walking/running, lounging, you could even set up a slack line between any of the large oak trees if you were so inclined.

A beautiful space that I now have wonderful memories of...go create some of your own!< /Review>< Pictures>
